          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Are orphan pages bad for SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Orphan pages waste crawl budget, receive zero internal link equity, and often remain unindexed. Even when Google discovers them through sitemaps, they rank poorly without internal link support because they carry no authority from the rest of the site.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many internal links should each page have?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>There is no fixed rule, but every valuable page should receive at least 2-3 contextual internal links from related content. Important pages should have more, and all pages should be reachable within three clicks from the homepage.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can an orphan page still rank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Rarely. If an orphan page has strong external backlinks or appears in an XML sitemap, Google may index and rank it. However, it will almost always underperform compared to a well-internally-linked page covering the same topic, because it receives no PageRank distribution from the site.</p></div></div>
          </div>
